## Scope

This slice owns the storage assembly's read/write behaviour over the Part A root aggregate: canonical JSON serialization, the published JSON Schema and validate-on-load, `.ocproj` file read/write, `.binz` sidecars for derived/bulk artefacts only, recent files and autosave, undo/redo of model edits, chart-data and chart-image export, and the report generator plus material-library import/export and design-history append/diff. The domain root and `$defs` are defined by Part A (and filled at field level by Parts B–H); this slice defines the serialization/validation/file-format/export/history/library-exchange behaviour over that root, the sole `StorageError` channel, and the destructive/long-running operator-UX commitments. Schema versioning, migration, backwards-compat shims, encryption, and cloud sync are out of scope; `Result<'T,'E>` is the only error channel.

## Requirements

The following are the parent's Part I directives, reproduced verbatim. Contractful identifiers and `<file>:<line>` references are preserved exactly.

### R-1 (I.1) [Core] — Canonical JSON serialization of the project root

`OpticalConstructor.Storage.fsproj` MUST provide a module `OpticalConstructor.Storage.ProjectJson` exposing `serializeProject : OpticalConstructorProject -> Result<string, StorageError>` and `deserializeProject : string -> Result<OpticalConstructorProject, StorageError>` over the Part A root aggregate `OpticalConstructorProject` (§A.7). Serialization MUST use **System.Text.Json with FSharp.SystemTextJson** (the package Part A admits) configured with `JsonFSharpOptions` so that F# records, discriminated unions (`ConstructorElement`, `BeamBranch`, `Substrate`, `Thickness`, `WaveLength`), and `option` values round-trip idiomatically; it MUST NOT use Newtonsoft or FsPickler for this path (binding rule 4).

Reuse before invention: do NOT hand-roll a JSON writer — the single primitive to reach for is `System.Text.Json.JsonSerializer.Serialize/Deserialize` with the `FSharp.SystemTextJson` converter registered once in a shared `JsonSerializerOptions` value. The serializer MUST write the domain model's canonical SI fields verbatim: `Thickness of double<meter>` (`Media.fs:12`) and `WaveLength.value : double<meter>` (`Fields.fs:284`) are emitted as their stored meter values; the human-facing unit travels only in the `unitOfMeasure` field (§A.7 `unitOfMeasure` `$def`). No unit conversion, rounding, or canonicalization of physical magnitudes occurs in this module.

`StorageError` MUST be a net-new DU in `OpticalConstructor.Storage.Errors` with cases at minimum `JsonParseError of string`, `SchemaValidationError of string list`, `SchemaMissing`, `FileIoError of exn`, `BinzError of exn`, and `SidecarMissing of string`. It MUST NOT wrap or shadow `Softellect.Sys.Errors`; it is the sole error channel for this part and is returned, never thrown.

### R-2 (I.2) [Core] — Published JSON Schema and validate-on-load

`OpticalConstructor.Storage.fsproj` MUST ship the file `schema/optical-constructor-project.schema.json` as a build-copied content item, carrying `"$id": "https://berreman/schema/optical-constructor-project.json"` and the `$defs` enumerated in §A.7 (`opticalSystem`, `layer`, `opticalProperties`, `beamNode`, `beamBranch`, `constructorElement`, `materialEntry`, `sourceSpec`, `unitOfMeasure`). This part authors the schema's **top-level envelope and the storage-owned `$defs`** (`materialEntry`, `sourceSpec`, `unitOfMeasure`, and the project root object: `schemaVersion` string, `systems`, `materials`, `sources`, `sweeps`, `chartSettings`, `beamTree`, plus optional `sidecars` array); the physics-shaped `$defs` (`opticalSystem`, `layer`, `opticalProperties`, `beamNode`, `beamBranch`, `constructorElement`) are filled by Parts B–G and MUST NOT be re-shaped here.

`deserializeProject` (I.1) MUST validate the parsed JSON document against this schema **before** binding it to `OpticalConstructorProject`, using **JsonSchema.Net** (the package Part A admits) — load the schema once into a `JsonSchema` value and call `Evaluate`. On any validation failure the function MUST return `SchemaValidationError` carrying the list of JsonSchema.Net evaluation messages and MUST NOT return a partially-bound project. If the schema content item is absent at runtime the function MUST return `SchemaMissing`. Schema **versioning and migration are out of scope**: a `schemaVersion` whose value does not equal the single shipped version MUST surface as `SchemaValidationError`, not trigger any migration code.

### R-3 (I.3) [Core] — Project file read/write with `.ocproj` extension

`OpticalConstructor.Storage.fsproj` MUST provide `ProjectFile` with `saveProject : string -> OpticalConstructorProject -> Result<unit, StorageError>` and `openProject : string -> Result<OpticalConstructorProject, StorageError>`. `saveProject` MUST serialize via `serializeProject` (I.1) and write the resulting UTF-8 text to the given path with the extension `.ocproj`; `openProject` MUST read the file, then call `deserializeProject` (I.2) so that schema validation always runs on load. All filesystem access MUST be wrapped so any exception becomes `FileIoError`; exceptions MUST NOT propagate out of these functions (project CLAUDE.md, `Result`-not-exceptions).

The canonical project is a single self-contained JSON text file — it MUST NOT be a zip, a folder bundle, or a multi-file container. Sidecars (I.4) live beside it as separate `.binz` files referenced by relative path from the JSON's `sidecars` array. `.ocproj` files are user documents and MUST NOT be added to any `.gitignore`; autosave and sidecar artefacts are addressed in I.5 and I.4 respectively. This `openProject` path is the single project-open seam every other part routes template loads and gallery loads through (Part J §J.3, §J.11).

### R-4 (I.4) [Core/Standard] — `.binz` sidecars for derived/bulk artefacts only

`OpticalConstructor.Storage.fsproj` MUST provide `Sidecar` with `writeSidecar<'T> : string -> 'T -> Result<unit, StorageError>` and `readSidecar<'T> : string -> Result<'T, StorageError>`, used **only** for derived/bulk artefacts: parametric-sweep result tables (the output of `calculate`/`calculate3D`, `Variables.fs:237,270` per Part A), in-layer field maps, and fit/design histories. These functions MUST reuse `Softellect.Sys.Core.serialize`/`deserialize` with `BinaryZippedFormat` (`C:/GitHub/Softellect/Sys/Core.fs:254,257`), and the file extension MUST be `.binz` (`Softellect.Sys.Primitives.fs:267`). Reuse is mandatory: do NOT introduce a second pickler, a second zip path, or a custom binary format — the one primitive to reach for is `Softellect.Sys.Core.serialize BinaryZippedFormat`.

`.binz` sidecars MUST NOT carry the canonical project definition or any hand/LLM-editable content (binding rule 4); attempting to serialize `OpticalConstructorProject` through `writeSidecar` is forbidden by directive and MUST NOT be done. Each sidecar is referenced from the project JSON only by **relative path** under the `sidecars` array (I.2); the schema MUST require those paths to be relative so a moved project folder keeps its sidecars. Sidecars are regenerable derived data and SHOULD be excluded from version control: this part's `files` list contributes a `.gitignore` entry for `*.binz` under the project working folder. Caching policies, sidecar eviction, and retention windows are OUT OF SCOPE.

### R-5 (I.5) [Standard] — Recent files and autosave

`OpticalConstructor.Storage.fsproj` MUST provide `RecentFiles` with `loadRecent : unit -> string list` and `pushRecent : string -> string list`, persisting the most-recently-used `.ocproj` paths (most-recent first, bounded list) to a single JSON preferences file in the per-user application-data folder, serialized through `serializeProject`'s shared `JsonSerializerOptions` (I.1) — no separate JSON stack. The recent-files list is the discoverability surface required by the Operator-facing UX checklist; the UI (Part J) renders it under File ▸ Recent.

`OpticalConstructor.Storage.fsproj` MUST provide `Autosave` with `autosavePath : string -> string` (deriving a sibling `<name>.ocproj.autosave` path) and `writeAutosave : string -> OpticalConstructorProject -> Result<unit, StorageError>`, reusing `serializeProject` (I.1) — autosave writes the **same canonical JSON**, never `.binz`. Autosave MUST write to the `.autosave` sidewrite path and MUST NOT overwrite the user's `.ocproj` until the user explicitly Saves; this satisfies the checklist's destructive-action gate by keeping the autosave file distinct from the committed document. The autosave timer interval and trigger are owned by the UI model (Part J §J.10); this part owns only the write function and the path derivation. `*.autosave` MUST be contributed to `.gitignore`. Retry-on-failure and rolling autosave generations are OUT OF SCOPE — a failed autosave returns `FileIoError` and the UI surfaces it.

### R-6 (I.6) [Standard] — Undo/redo of model edits

`OpticalConstructor.Storage.fsproj` MUST provide `History` with an immutable type `EditHistory` holding `past : OpticalConstructorProject list`, `present : OpticalConstructorProject`, and `future : OpticalConstructorProject list`, plus `push : OpticalConstructorProject -> EditHistory -> EditHistory`, `undo : EditHistory -> EditHistory`, and `redo : EditHistory -> EditHistory`. The structure MUST be immutable F# (project CLAUDE.md) and MUST NOT use `.Value`/`.IsSome`; `undo`/`redo` MUST pattern-match the `past`/`future` lists and MUST be no-ops (return the input unchanged) when the respective list is empty. This satisfies the Operator-facing UX checklist's opposing-action/undo requirement: every destructive model edit in the UI pushes onto `EditHistory`, and `undo` is its inverse. This is the multi-level undo/redo history that Part B §B.10 defers here; the construction page's single-level snapshot swap is the degenerate one-deep case.

Undo/redo holds **whole-project snapshots** in memory; persistent on-disk undo journals, command-pattern diff logs, and bounded-history eviction are OUT OF SCOPE for this directive (the design-history file in I.8 is the durable record). The history depth bound, if any, is owned by the UI model (Part J).

### R-7 (I.7) [Standard] — Chart-data and chart-image export

`OpticalConstructor.Storage.fsproj` MUST provide `Export` with `exportCsv : string -> (string list * float[][]) -> Result<unit, StorageError>` writing sweep results as comma-separated rows (header row of column names, then numeric rows) and `exportExcel : string -> (string list * float[][]) -> Result<unit, StorageError>` writing an `.xlsx` workbook. The CSV column data MUST be the same sweep tuples produced by the engine's `calculate`/`calculate3D` (`Variables.fs:237,270` per Part A) and rendered to charts by `plot`/`plotComparison`/`plot3D` (`Charting.fs:21,38,64`); this part serializes that already-computed data and MUST NOT re-run or re-implement the solver. Excel export MUST use the existing in-tree XLSX dependency if one is referenced by `Analytics.fsproj`; if none is, ClosedXML MUST be added as the single Excel package reference (no new Excel abstraction layer).

Chart **image** export to PNG/SVG/PDF MUST be delegated to the chart libraries Part A names, not re-implemented: Plotly.NET charts (the engine's `Charting.fs` path, `Chart.show` at `Charting.fs:34`) export through Plotly.NET's image writer hosted in WebView2 (Part A UI stack), and ScottPlot charts export through ScottPlot's own `SavePng`/`SaveSvg`. `Export` MUST expose `exportChartImage : string -> ChartImageFormat -> ChartHandle -> Result<unit, StorageError>` where `ChartImageFormat = Png | Svg | Pdf` is a net-new DU and `ChartHandle` is the UI-supplied chart object; this function dispatches to the owning library's save call and MUST NOT rasterize or vectorize charts itself. The Operator-facing UX checklist's progress/completion contract for export: each `export*` function returns `Result` on completion, and the UI refreshes the results pane and offers "Open containing folder" on `Ok`.

### R-8 (I.8) [Standard] — Report generator, material library import/export, design history & diff

`OpticalConstructor.Storage.fsproj` MUST provide `Report.generate : ReportFormat -> OpticalConstructorProject -> ChartHandle list -> Result<unit, StorageError>` producing a single PDF or HTML document (`ReportFormat = Pdf | Html`, net-new DU) containing the stack schematic, the project parameters read from `OpticalConstructorProject` (§A.7), the supplied chart images (via I.7's `exportChartImage`), and any fit-result summary present on the project. HTML report assembly MUST reuse the engine's existing Giraffe.ViewEngine usage (`Charting.fs:9` imports `Giraffe.ViewEngine`; `createDescription` builds `h1`/`h2` nodes at `Charting.fs:13`) rather than introducing a second HTML builder; PDF output MUST be produced by printing that HTML through the same Plotly/WebView2 PDF path used in I.7. The report render is the long-running action in this part: `generate` returns `Result` on completion and the UI (Part J) shows determinate progress per included chart and refreshes to offer the produced file.

`OpticalConstructor.Storage.fsproj` MUST provide `MaterialLibrary` with `importMaterials : string -> Result<MaterialEntry list, StorageError>` and `exportMaterials : string -> MaterialEntry list -> Result<unit, StorageError>` over the §A.7 `materialEntry` `$def`. Export MUST write the canonical JSON (validated against the `materialEntry` `$def`, I.2) so a library file is itself schema-checked. Import MUST accept that same JSON **and** refractiveindex.info-style external tabulated/CSV data via **FSharp.Data** (the package Part A admits) — FSharp.Data is the single primitive to reach for parsing external CSV/measurement data; do NOT hand-roll a CSV reader. Imported n,k tables map onto the engine's dispersion types (`OpticalPropertiesWithDisp`, `Dispersion.fs:53` per Part A) — the mapping rules are owned by Part D (§D.9) and MUST NOT be redefined here; this part owns only the file read and the `MaterialEntry list` boundary. This is the shareable material-library file format that Part D §D.8 defers here.

`OpticalConstructor.Storage.fsproj` MUST provide `DesignHistory` with `appendRevision : string -> OpticalConstructorProject -> Result<unit, StorageError>` and `diffRevisions : OpticalConstructorProject -> OpticalConstructorProject -> ProjectDiff` (net-new `ProjectDiff` record listing added/removed/changed systems, layers, materials, and sources by stable identity). `appendRevision` MUST persist each revision as a numbered canonical-JSON snapshot under a `history/` folder beside the `.ocproj`, reusing `serializeProject` (I.1) — revisions are JSON, not `.binz`, because they remain hand/LLM-readable (binding rule 4). `diffRevisions` MUST be a pure F# function comparing two already-loaded project values and MUST NOT shell out to git or any external VCS. Full branching/merge version control is OUT OF SCOPE; the committed scope is append-only revision snapshots plus structural diff, matching 010 §7's "design history & diff" [Standard] bullet.

## Non-requirements

- The `OpticalConstructorProject` aggregate and the `$defs` are defined by Part A (slice 001) and filled at field level by Parts B/C/E/H (slices 003/004/005/008); this part authors the top-level envelope and storage-owned `$defs` only, and MUST NOT re-shape the physics `$defs`.
- The material n,k→`OpticalPropertiesWithDisp` mapping rules are owned by Part D §D.9 (slice 002); §I.8's `importMaterials` owns only the file read and the `MaterialEntry list` boundary.
- The autosave timer/trigger and the chart `ChartHandle` objects are owned by the UI (Part J slice 010 / Part H slice 008); this part owns the write functions and dispatch only.
- Schema versioning, migration code, backwards-compat shims, multi-format converters, encryption, cloud sync, retry layers, caching/eviction (§0 constraint 6; I.0).
- Chart rendering itself is owned by Part H (slice 008); export delegates to the chart libraries' own writers and MUST NOT rasterize/vectorize.

